WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:29.000
British and American Festivities by Gina Klemmer.

00:29.000 --> 00:52.000
My Gina Klemmer.

00:52.000 --> 01:00.000
Introduction How much do you know about British and American Festivities?

01:00.000 --> 01:06.000
Do you know that ancient pagan customs are still part of some festivities?

01:06.000 --> 01:14.000
This book tells you about the most important festivities of the year, their origins and how they are celebrated.

01:14.000 --> 01:21.000
You will notice that some festivities are celebrated only in Great Britain and others only in America.

01:21.000 --> 01:27.000
You will also notice that Americans love big celebrations with parades and marching bands.

01:27.000 --> 01:38.000
If you want to know more about a festivity, you can contact the Internet sites listed on page 112.

01:38.000 --> 01:46.000
Chapter 1 Columbus Day The second Monday of October is Columbus Day.

01:46.000 --> 01:53.000
This festivity is celebrated only in the United States of America. Why?

01:53.000 --> 01:58.000
During Christopher Columbus' time, people thought the world was flat.

01:58.000 --> 02:07.000
Columbus was born in Genoa, a beautiful Italian city on the northwest coast.

02:07.000 --> 02:11.000
For many years he watched ships leave the port of Genoa.

02:11.000 --> 02:19.000
He noticed that these ships seemed to go under the horizon.

02:19.000 --> 02:24.000
He was convinced that the world was round, but no one believed him.

02:24.000 --> 02:29.000
He wanted to reach the east by sailing to the west.

02:29.000 --> 02:34.000
Queen Isabella and King Ferdinand of Spain believed Columbus' theory.

02:34.000 --> 02:43.000
They gave him three ships, the Santa Maria, the Nina and the Pinta, to travel and test this theory.

02:43.000 --> 02:54.000
Columbus was an expert navigator. After a long and difficult voyage, he and his men reached the North American continent on the 12th of October 1492.

02:54.000 --> 02:59.000
The famous Italian explorer discovered the New World.

02:59.000 --> 03:07.000
After his great discovery, a new era of exploration began, and America was born.

03:07.000 --> 03:15.000
Today most Americans celebrate Columbus Day with colorful parades, and they elect a Columbus Day queen.

03:15.000 --> 03:23.000
The parade is usually long with big floats dedicated to Columbus, and there are other multicultural floats too.

03:23.000 --> 03:28.000
After the parade there is usually a dinner and dance.

03:28.000 --> 03:35.000
In San Francisco, California, there is also a reenactment of Columbus' discovery.

03:35.000 --> 03:42.000
A man dresses up as Columbus, and several other men dress up as his sailors.

03:42.000 --> 03:48.000
They get into a boat and row to the beach.

03:48.000 --> 03:53.000
When they get out of their boat, they kneel on the beach and thank God.

03:53.000 --> 04:00.000
Americans enjoy remembering the great navigator.

04:00.000 --> 04:09.000
Chapter 2 Halloween Halloween is celebrated on the 31st of October.

04:09.000 --> 04:14.000
It is an exciting event in the United States and in Great Britain.

04:14.000 --> 04:19.000
Every American calendar has Halloween marked on it.

04:19.000 --> 04:22.000
Halloween has ancient Celtic origins.

04:22.000 --> 04:32.000
On the Celtic calendar, sound was the last day of summer and the last day of the year, the 31st of October.

04:32.000 --> 04:39.000
The Celtic priests, called druids, practice religious rituals and magic on sound.

04:39.000 --> 04:42.000
They also predicted the future.

04:42.000 --> 04:47.000
On this day, the Celts made big fires and dressed in scary costumes.

04:47.000 --> 04:52.000
They wanted to frighten the evil spirits.

04:52.000 --> 04:56.000
They dressed as ghosts, skeletons and witches.

04:56.000 --> 05:06.000
They believed that ghosts came out of their tombs on the night of the 31st of October.

05:06.000 --> 05:14.000
Sound also became a harvest festival after the Roman invasion of Britain in 43 A.D.

05:14.000 --> 05:18.000
Christian practices replaced pagan practices.

05:18.000 --> 05:27.000
The Christians called the 1st of November all Hallows Day, the day of all saints.

05:27.000 --> 05:33.000
The evening of the 31st of October was called all Hallows Eve.

05:33.000 --> 05:37.000
This became Halloween.

05:37.000 --> 05:44.000
At Halloween, American children in elementary schools take their costumes and masks to school.

05:44.000 --> 05:52.000
Typical Halloween costumes are the witch, ghost, skeleton, monster, vampire or alien.

05:52.000 --> 05:57.000
Young people have fun making their own costumes, but some prefer to buy them.

05:57.000 --> 06:03.000
In the afternoon, the children put on their costumes and have a Halloween party at school.

06:03.000 --> 06:10.000
Schools are decorated with pumpkins, ghosts, witches and bats.

06:10.000 --> 06:15.000
It is a popular tradition to make jack-o-lanterns out of pumpkins.

06:15.000 --> 06:19.000
People put them in front of the windows of their homes.

06:19.000 --> 06:23.000
The jack-o-lantern is of Celtic origin too.

06:23.000 --> 06:27.000
There are funny Halloween games, such as bobbing for apples.

06:27.000 --> 06:36.000
Favourite Halloween foods are candied apples, nuts, licorice, popcorn and pumpkin pie.

06:36.000 --> 06:40.000
American teenagers have a Halloween party in the evening.

06:40.000 --> 06:46.000
The party is usually in the school gymnasium and everyone wears a costume and mask.

06:46.000 --> 06:50.000
The best costume usually wins a prize.

06:50.000 --> 06:56.000
In the 19th century, Irish immigrants took their Halloween customs to the United States.

06:56.000 --> 07:00.000
They introduced the custom of trick or treating.

07:00.000 --> 07:06.000
American and British children and teenagers go trick or treating on Halloween evening.

07:06.000 --> 07:13.000
They go from house to house in their costumes and ring doorbells.

07:13.000 --> 07:17.000
When the door opens, they shout, trick or treat!

07:17.000 --> 07:20.000
People usually give them sweets or money.

07:20.000 --> 07:23.000
If not, the children play a trick.

07:23.000 --> 07:32.000
They write on windows with soap or spray shaving cream on cars and people.

07:32.000 --> 07:37.000
Chapter 3. Guy Fawkes night

07:37.000 --> 07:43.000
The 5th of November is Guy Fawkes night or bonfire night.

07:43.000 --> 07:47.000
This is a British festivity.

07:47.000 --> 07:53.000
The story of Guy Fawkes goes back to the early 1600s.

07:53.000 --> 08:01.000
During this period, there were religious problems between Protestants and Catholics in Britain.

08:01.000 --> 08:09.000
King James I was a Protestant and he passed severe laws against Catholics.

08:10.000 --> 08:15.000
They were not permitted to have religious services.

08:15.000 --> 08:24.000
A group of 12 Catholics decided to kill King James I and destroy the Parliament building.

08:24.000 --> 08:34.000
They planned to blow up the houses of Parliament on the 5th of November 1605 when the king was present.

08:34.000 --> 08:38.000
This was called the gunpowder plot.

08:38.000 --> 08:42.000
The leader of the plot was Robert Catesby.

08:42.000 --> 08:51.000
The plotters put 30 barrels of explosives in the cellars under the Parliament building.

08:51.000 --> 08:56.000
Guy Fawkes was an expert with explosives.

08:56.000 --> 09:06.000
His responsibility was to guard the barrels of explosives and light the fuse on the 5th of November.

09:06.000 --> 09:10.000
The king's soldiers discovered the plot.

09:10.000 --> 09:15.000
Guy Fawkes was immediately arrested and tortured.

09:15.000 --> 09:19.000
The other plotters were found three days later.

09:19.000 --> 09:24.000
Guy Fawkes and the others were hanged.

09:24.000 --> 09:35.000
On the night of the 5th of November 1605, many people in London were happy because the plot was discovered.

09:36.000 --> 09:41.000
To celebrate, they started bonfires in the street.

09:41.000 --> 09:48.000
Someone made an effigy of Guy Fawkes and burnt it.

09:48.000 --> 09:55.000
Ever since that day, the British have celebrated Guy Fawkes night.

09:55.000 --> 10:03.000
Today, young people in Britain make a guy with old clothes and fill him with newspaper.

10:03.000 --> 10:10.000
Then they go around the streets with the guy and ask for a penny for the guy.

10:10.000 --> 10:15.000
With this money, they buy fireworks.

10:15.000 --> 10:23.000
On the night of the 5th of November, there are fireworks and big bonfires to burn the guy.

10:23.000 --> 10:27.000
Some people have bonfires in their back gardens.

10:27.000 --> 10:38.000
Young people love the noise, excitement and colorful fireworks.

10:38.000 --> 10:43.000
On this night, they eat toffee apples.

10:43.000 --> 10:49.000
In Lewis, Sussex, there is a big public festival on Guy Fawkes night.

10:49.000 --> 10:53.000
People dress in historic costumes.

10:53.000 --> 10:59.000
The guy is burnt on top of a hill on an enormous bonfire.

10:59.000 --> 11:03.000
There are also brilliant fireworks.

11:09.000 --> 11:14.000
Here is a rhyme about Guy Fawkes.

11:14.000 --> 11:22.000
Remember, remember the 5th of November, gunpowder, treason and plot.

11:22.000 --> 11:32.000
I see no reason why gunpowder and treason should ever be forgot.

11:32.000 --> 11:37.000
Chapter 4. Thanksgiving

11:37.000 --> 11:46.000
Thanksgiving is a very important American festivity, and it is celebrated on the last Thursday of November.

11:46.000 --> 11:52.000
However, schools and many shops and offices are closed for four days.

11:52.000 --> 11:57.000
Thursday, Friday, Saturday and Sunday.

11:57.000 --> 12:04.000
Thanksgiving is a special day for families to be together and to thank God for all they have.

12:04.000 --> 12:10.000
Americans travel great distances to be with their families on this occasion.

12:10.000 --> 12:15.000
Why is thanksgiving such an important day?

12:15.000 --> 12:21.000
The tradition started with the pilgrims, the founders of America.

12:21.000 --> 12:28.000
The pilgrims left Great Britain in 1620 because of religious persecution.

12:28.000 --> 12:36.000
They wanted to start a new life in America and practice their religion in freedom.

12:36.000 --> 12:43.000
100 men, women and children left Britain on a small ship called the Mayflower.

12:43.000 --> 12:53.000
Their sea voyage was very difficult. Many pilgrims died during the voyage.

12:53.000 --> 13:01.000
They arrived on the northeast coast of North America in December 1620 and founded Plymouth.

13:01.000 --> 13:10.000
The area was a wilderness. It was almost winter and they had no homes and little food.

13:10.000 --> 13:19.000
They immediately built small homes, but it was too late to cultivate crops.

13:19.000 --> 13:29.000
The winter was very cold and harsh. Almost half of the pilgrims died because their living conditions were very bad.

13:29.000 --> 13:35.000
The friendly Wampanoag Indians helped them during the long winter.

13:35.000 --> 13:41.000
In the spring, the pilgrims met an Indian called Squanto.

13:41.000 --> 13:47.000
He explained how to grow corn, hunt and live in the wilderness.

13:47.000 --> 13:53.000
Soon the pilgrims and the Indians became good friends.

13:53.000 --> 14:00.000
The pilgrims worked hard and cultivated crops. The summer harvest was excellent.

14:00.000 --> 14:09.000
By November 1621, everyone had food and a home. There was hope for the future.

14:09.000 --> 14:19.000
Governor William Bradford, the pilgrim leader, decided to celebrate with the dinner for the pilgrims and the Indians.

14:19.000 --> 14:29.000
He wanted to give thanks to God. This was the first Thanksgiving dinner and it lasted for three days.

14:29.000 --> 14:35.000
Today, the traditional Thanksgiving meal is similar to the first.

14:35.000 --> 14:42.000
People eat roast turkey, sweet potatoes, corn, cranberry sauce and pumpkin pie.

14:42.000 --> 14:47.000
Most families start the meal with a prayer.

14:47.000 --> 14:53.000
The long Thanksgiving weekend is the perfect time to start Christmas shopping.

14:53.000 --> 15:03.000
Big stores and shops are open on Friday, Saturday and Sunday for the Christmas shoppers.

15:03.000 --> 15:09.000
5. Christmas

15:09.000 --> 15:19.000
On the 25th of December, Great Britain and the United States and many other countries celebrate Christmas.

15:19.000 --> 15:27.000
The word Christmas comes from the Old English Christes Messe, Christ's math.

15:27.000 --> 15:32.000
On this day, Christians celebrate the birth of Christ.

15:32.000 --> 15:38.000
Kindness and giving are the spirit of Christmas.

15:38.000 --> 15:48.000
Charles Dickens, the famous British writer, wrote a Christmas Carol, a story about the true meaning of Christmas.

15:48.000 --> 15:54.000
Why is Christmas celebrated on the 25th of December?

15:54.000 --> 15:59.000
Christmas comes from two pagan festivals.

15:59.000 --> 16:06.000
People celebrated the winter solstice on the 21st or 22nd of December.

16:06.000 --> 16:18.000
The Roman emperors chose the 25th of December as the birthday of the sun, Natalith Solith.

16:18.000 --> 16:26.000
After the winter solstice, the days become longer and the sun is higher in the sky.

16:26.000 --> 16:31.000
In ancient Rome, this was the season of Saturnalia.

16:31.000 --> 16:35.000
Saturnalia was a time of merrymaking.

16:35.000 --> 16:41.000
During Saturnalia, the Romans exchanged presents.

16:41.000 --> 16:49.000
The pagan tribes of Northern Europe enjoyed a 12-day winter festival called Yule.

16:49.000 --> 16:58.000
Yule had its own traditions of Yule cakes, fir trees, holly, mistletoe and presents.

16:58.000 --> 17:03.000
Birthories and holly are still a symbol of Christmas.

17:03.000 --> 17:08.000
Today, a branch of mistletoe in the house has another meaning.

17:08.000 --> 17:14.000
When a boy and girl meet under the mistletoe, they usually kiss.

17:14.000 --> 17:21.000
The custom of kissing under the mistletoe is an ancient Celtic rite.

17:21.000 --> 17:25.000
Medieval Christmas was a long event.

17:25.000 --> 17:30.000
It lasted 12 days, like the Yule festival.

17:30.000 --> 17:38.000
Celebration started on the 25th of December and ended on the night of the 6th of January.

17:38.000 --> 17:44.000
Christmas is the biggest holiday on the American and British calendar.

17:44.000 --> 17:49.000
However, in Scotland, New Year is more important.

17:49.000 --> 17:59.000
In Great Britain and the United States, people prepare for Christmas weeks before the 25th of December.

17:59.000 --> 18:04.000
Cities and towns are beautifully decorated with Christmas symbols.

18:04.000 --> 18:11.000
The Christmas tree, Santa Claus, colorful lights and much more.

18:11.000 --> 18:15.000
Shop windows are full of presents for everyone.

18:15.000 --> 18:18.000
People are busy buying presents.

18:18.000 --> 18:21.000
There are Santa clauses everywhere.

18:21.000 --> 18:26.000
On street corners, people sing Christmas carols.

18:26.000 --> 18:31.000
In Britain, many children go carol singing with an adult.

18:31.000 --> 18:35.000
They go from house to house and sing.

18:35.000 --> 18:39.000
They usually receive money for their singing.

18:39.000 --> 18:43.000
They use this money to buy presents.

18:43.000 --> 18:47.000
There is a joyous atmosphere.

18:48.000 --> 18:56.000
Christmas today respects many of the old traditions and has added new ones.

18:56.000 --> 19:02.000
The modern Christmas tree originated in western Germany long ago.

19:02.000 --> 19:10.000
The Germans put up a fir tree in their homes and decorated it with biscuits and candles.

19:10.000 --> 19:16.000
German settlers took this tradition to North America in the 17th century.

19:16.000 --> 19:23.000
By the 19th century, Christmas trees were very popular in the United States.

19:23.000 --> 19:30.000
In Britain, the Christmas tree became popular after 1840.

19:30.000 --> 19:39.000
The German prince Albert, Queen Victoria's husband, took the Christmas tree to the British royal family.

19:39.000 --> 19:44.000
Soon, the Christmas tree became popular all over Great Britain.

19:44.000 --> 19:50.000
There is a big tree every year in Trafalgar Square, London.

19:50.000 --> 19:58.000
Today, America's most famous Christmas tree is in the Rockefeller Center, New York City.

19:58.000 --> 20:05.000
The Empire State Building in New York City is one of the tallest buildings in the world.

20:05.000 --> 20:12.000
At Christmas, the top of the building is illuminated with red and green lights.

20:12.000 --> 20:20.000
Today, almost every Christian family has a decorated Christmas tree at home or in the garden.

20:20.000 --> 20:28.000
Some families put up the tree on Christmas Eve and others put it up at the beginning of December.

20:28.000 --> 20:34.000
Many families put a nativity scene under the Christmas tree.

20:34.000 --> 20:42.000
St. Francis of Assisi created the first nativity scene in the 1200s.

20:42.000 --> 20:47.000
Many Americans wear Christmas clothes during the Christmas season.

20:47.000 --> 20:53.000
These are clothes with Christmas colors and symbols.

20:53.000 --> 20:57.000
Christmas crackers are an old tradition.

20:57.000 --> 21:00.000
They were invented in London.

21:00.000 --> 21:06.000
Two people pull the cracker until it bangs and opens.

21:06.000 --> 21:14.000
Inside, there is usually a small present, a paper hat and a joke.

21:14.000 --> 21:20.000
In the United States, there are Christmas shops in many cities.

21:20.000 --> 21:27.000
They sell all types of Christmas trees, ornaments and other decorations for the home.

21:27.000 --> 21:36.000
Christmas shops are open all year long, so you can buy your Christmas tree in June.

21:36.000 --> 21:41.000
It is usual to send Christmas cards to relatives and friends.

21:41.000 --> 21:50.000
The first Christmas card was designed in Britain by John Calcut Horsley in 1843.

21:50.000 --> 21:55.000
A thousand copies of the card were printed in London.

21:55.000 --> 21:59.000
The design was a family party with the words,

21:59.000 --> 22:03.000
A Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year to you.

22:03.000 --> 22:11.000
In the mid-19th century, a shop owner in Albany, New York made a card that said,

22:11.000 --> 22:16.000
Christmas greetings from Pease's Great Variety Store.

22:16.000 --> 22:23.000
This was the beginning of the big Christmas card industry.

22:24.000 --> 22:32.000
The figure of Santa Claus comes from St. Nicholas, a fourth-century Christian bishop of Asia Minor.

22:32.000 --> 22:37.000
He was famous for his generosity and kindness.

22:37.000 --> 22:46.000
The Dutch settlers of New York brought the tradition of sinter class, Santa Claus to America.

22:46.000 --> 22:53.000
Father Christmas, or Santa Claus, is an important part of the Christmas tradition.

22:53.000 --> 22:59.000
Children write letters to him and ask for special presents.

22:59.000 --> 23:07.000
Today we see Santa Claus as an old man with a white beard dressed in a red suit.

23:07.000 --> 23:15.000
He drives a sleigh pulled by reindeer and comes down the chimney with toys for the children.

23:15.000 --> 23:26.000
This image of Santa Claus was created by the American cartoonist Thomas Nast in 1863.

23:26.000 --> 23:31.000
American and British children put out a stocking on Christmas Eve,

23:31.000 --> 23:36.000
because they hope to receive presents from Santa Claus.

23:36.000 --> 23:43.000
Then they go to bed early, because they want Santa Claus to come.

23:43.000 --> 23:53.000
Many Christians go to church services at midnight and others go on Christmas morning.

23:53.000 --> 23:58.000
Christmas presents are usually opened on Christmas morning.

23:58.000 --> 24:05.000
After Christmas dinner, many families listen to the traditional Queen's speech in Britain

24:05.000 --> 24:09.000
and watch special Christmas television programs.

24:09.000 --> 24:14.000
Children play with their new toys.

24:14.000 --> 24:21.000
In Britain, some people go for a Christmas day swim in the sea or in a lake.

24:21.000 --> 24:31.000
In Hyde Park in London, some courageous people swim in the serpentine.

24:31.000 --> 24:38.000
The First Noel

24:38.000 --> 24:47.000
The angel did say was to certain poor shepherds in fields as they lay.

24:47.000 --> 24:57.000
In fields where they lay, keeping their sheep on a cold winter's night that was so deep.

24:57.000 --> 25:03.000
