26:47.000 --> 26:50.000
Oh come, let us adore him.

26:50.000 --> 26:53.000
Oh come, let us adore him.

26:53.000 --> 26:56.000
Christ the Lord.

26:57.000 --> 27:00.000
God of God.

27:00.000 --> 27:03.000
Light of light.

27:03.000 --> 27:09.000
Lo, ye abose not the virgin's womb.

27:09.000 --> 27:15.000
Very God, big God and not created.

27:15.000 --> 27:18.000
Oh come, let us adore him.

27:18.000 --> 27:21.000
Oh come, let us adore him.

27:21.000 --> 27:24.000
Come, let us adore him.

27:24.000 --> 27:27.000
Christ the Lord.

27:27.000 --> 27:30.000
Sing choirs of angels.

27:30.000 --> 27:33.000
Sing in exaltation.

27:33.000 --> 27:39.000
Sing all ye citizens of heaven above.

27:39.000 --> 27:45.000
Glory to God in the highest.

27:45.000 --> 27:48.000
Oh come, let us adore him.

27:48.000 --> 27:51.000
Oh come, let us adore him.

27:51.000 --> 27:54.000
Oh come, let us adore him.

27:54.000 --> 27:58.000
Christ the Lord.

28:05.000 --> 28:12.000
Chapter 6 New Years Eve

28:12.000 --> 28:15.000
On the 31st of December,

28:15.000 --> 28:18.000
everyone celebrates the end of the old year

28:18.000 --> 28:21.000
and the beginning of the new.

28:21.000 --> 28:26.000
In Scotland, New Year's Eve is called Hogmane.

28:26.000 --> 28:30.000
It is the most important celebration of the year.

28:30.000 --> 28:34.000
In Edinburgh, there is an immense street celebration

28:34.000 --> 28:37.000
on New Year's Eve.

28:37.000 --> 28:42.000
In America and Britain, many people like going to parties

28:42.000 --> 28:46.000
or organizing them in their homes.

28:46.000 --> 28:51.000
Some people prefer to celebrate in restaurants or night clubs.

28:51.000 --> 28:56.000
Young people celebrate at home or at a disco.

28:56.000 --> 29:01.000
Others go to masked balls in costumes and masks.

29:01.000 --> 29:07.000
Everyone takes off their mask at midnight.

29:07.000 --> 29:11.000
Cheers, noise, music, dancing,

29:11.000 --> 29:14.000
colorful decorations, festive food and drink

29:14.000 --> 29:21.000
are all part of New Year's Eve.

29:21.000 --> 29:26.000
People like throwing confetti on the last night of the year.

29:26.000 --> 29:32.000
People wear their best party clothes on this exciting night.

29:32.000 --> 29:38.000
At parties, everyone wears funny paper hats and blows toy horns.

29:38.000 --> 29:42.000
Parties usually begin after 9pm

29:42.000 --> 29:45.000
and continue until the next morning.

29:45.000 --> 29:49.000
At midnight, everyone joins hands

29:49.000 --> 29:52.000
and sings the old Scottish song,

29:52.000 --> 29:55.000
Old Langsein.

29:56.000 --> 30:01.000
Should old acquaintance be forgotten

30:01.000 --> 30:04.000
and ever brought to mind?

30:04.000 --> 30:07.000
Should old acquaintance be forgotten

30:07.000 --> 30:10.000
for the sake of old Langsein?

30:10.000 --> 30:14.000
For old Langsein, my dear,

30:14.000 --> 30:20.000
for old Langsein will take a cup of kindness

30:20.000 --> 30:24.000
yet for the sake of old Langsein.

30:27.000 --> 30:29.000
In New York City,

30:29.000 --> 30:34.000
a favorite place to go on New Year's Eve is Times Square.

30:34.000 --> 30:41.000
At midnight, the words Happy New Year appear on an electronic sign.

30:44.000 --> 30:46.000
Bells and sirens ring,

30:46.000 --> 30:50.000
people cheer and there is a lot of noise.

30:57.000 --> 31:03.000
In London, many people go to celebrate in Trafalgar Square.

31:03.000 --> 31:08.000
Everyone in Britain waits for Big Ben to strike midnight.

31:08.000 --> 31:11.000
Then there is a lot of noise.

31:11.000 --> 31:14.000
People sing, Old Langsein,

31:14.000 --> 31:17.000
kiss each other and cheer.

31:17.000 --> 31:21.000
When we make a lot of noise on New Year's Eve,

31:21.000 --> 31:24.000
we are following ancient traditions.

31:24.000 --> 31:32.000
Ancient civilizations made noise to frighten evil spirits of the past year.

31:32.000 --> 31:34.000
On New Year's Eve,

31:34.000 --> 31:40.000
the Americans and the British make New Year's resolutions or promises.

31:41.000 --> 31:47.000
They promise to get rid of bad habits during the New Year.

31:47.000 --> 31:51.000
Some typical children's resolutions are,

31:51.000 --> 31:54.000
I resolve to do my homework,

31:54.000 --> 31:59.000
or I resolve to clean my room every day.

31:59.000 --> 32:03.000
Children write down their New Year's resolutions,

32:03.000 --> 32:09.000
sign their name and give the paper to their parents.

32:09.000 --> 32:13.000
Some typical adults' resolutions are,

32:13.000 --> 32:16.000
I resolve to stop smoking,

32:16.000 --> 32:20.000
or I resolve to go on a diet.

32:20.000 --> 32:26.000
Most people don't keep their promises, but a few do.

32:26.000 --> 32:29.000
In some American cities,

32:29.000 --> 32:36.000
office workers throw their old calendars out of the office windows on the 31st of December.

32:36.000 --> 32:40.000
They are throwing the old year away.

32:40.000 --> 32:45.000
It is incredible to see so much paper flying about.

32:45.000 --> 32:52.000
By 5.30 pm, the streets are covered with office calendars.

32:52.000 --> 32:54.000
At the end of the year,

32:54.000 --> 32:59.000
astrologists predict the future for all the signs of the zodiac.

32:59.000 --> 33:06.000
Some astrologists predict catastrophic events.

33:06.000 --> 33:12.000
Exercise 3, page 57.

33:12.000 --> 33:16.000
Listen to the dictation carefully.

33:16.000 --> 33:19.000
Then, listen to it again,

33:19.000 --> 33:25.000
and fill in the gaps with the correct word.

33:25.000 --> 33:33.000
People like going to parties on New Year's Eve.

33:33.000 --> 33:39.000
They wear their best party clothes.

33:39.000 --> 33:44.000
There is a lot of noise everywhere.

33:44.000 --> 33:52.000
People dance, sing, eat and drink.

33:52.000 --> 34:00.000
At midnight, bells ring and people cheer.

34:00.000 --> 34:10.000
In Edinburgh, Scotland, there is a big street celebration.

34:10.000 --> 34:13.000
At the end of the year,

34:13.000 --> 34:16.000
astrologists predict the future,

34:16.000 --> 34:24.000
and some people make New Year's resolutions.

34:24.000 --> 34:29.000
Chapter 7, New Year's Day.

34:29.000 --> 34:32.000
Happy New Year!

34:32.000 --> 34:35.000
The same to you and many more!

34:35.000 --> 34:43.000
This familiar greeting is heard throughout Britain and the United States on the 1st of January.

34:43.000 --> 34:47.000
People have always celebrated the New Year.

34:47.000 --> 34:53.000
In ancient civilizations, the calendar was based on the seasons.

34:53.000 --> 34:59.000
The Egyptian New Year began when the Nile River overflowed.

34:59.000 --> 35:03.000
For the early Britons and the Romans,

35:03.000 --> 35:08.000
the New Year began on the first day of spring.

35:08.000 --> 35:14.000
In 45 BC, the Roman Emperor Julius Caesar

35:14.000 --> 35:18.000
created a calendar with the 1st of January

35:18.000 --> 35:22.000
as the first day of the New Year.

35:22.000 --> 35:26.000
This calendar is still used today.

35:26.000 --> 35:30.000
January comes from Janus,

35:30.000 --> 35:35.000
the Roman god of beginnings and endings.

35:35.000 --> 35:39.000
New Year's traditions come from different cultures.

35:39.000 --> 35:45.000
Many people give presents and send cards on New Year's Day.

35:45.000 --> 35:49.000
This was part of a Roman and Old English tradition.

35:49.000 --> 35:56.000
Shops and offices give calendars and small presents to their clients.

35:56.000 --> 36:02.000
In Britain, most families have a big lunch and spend a quiet day at home.

36:02.000 --> 36:08.000
In the United States, many families have open house on New Year's Day.

36:08.000 --> 36:12.000
It is a custom introduced by George Washington,

36:12.000 --> 36:15.000
the first president of the United States.

36:15.000 --> 36:21.000
During open house, the front door of your home is open all day long.

36:21.000 --> 36:25.000
Friends and relatives come to say, Happy New Year!

36:25.000 --> 36:29.000
They eat and drink something, and then leave.

36:29.000 --> 36:35.000
Many clubs and organizations have open house too.

36:35.000 --> 36:40.000
On New Year's Day, most of the United States is covered with snow.

36:40.000 --> 36:46.000
However, in California and in the southern states, it is warm and sunny.

36:46.000 --> 36:52.000
In these sunny places, there are parades and football games.

36:52.000 --> 36:56.000
These football games are called bowl games.

36:56.000 --> 37:02.000
Each region has its parade and football game.

37:02.000 --> 37:06.000
Rose Bowl in Pasadena, California.

37:06.000 --> 37:10.000
Orange Bowl in Miami, Florida.

37:10.000 --> 37:14.000
Cotton Bowl in Dallas, Texas.

37:14.000 --> 37:19.000
Sugar Bowl in New Orleans, Louisiana.

37:20.000 --> 37:28.000
The Pasadena Tournament of Roses Parade is the biggest and oldest New Year's Day event.

37:28.000 --> 37:33.000
In Pasadena, more than 3 million people go to watch the parade.

37:33.000 --> 37:39.000
More than 70 million Americans watch it on television.

37:39.000 --> 37:46.000
Every year, there are about 60 spectacular floats made of fresh flowers.

37:46.000 --> 37:50.000
These floats show favorite storybook characters and animals.

37:50.000 --> 38:00.000
The queen of the parade is called the Citrus Queen, because so many citrus fruits grow in southern California.

38:00.000 --> 38:06.000
It takes about a year to organize the Pasadena Tournament of Roses Parade.

38:06.000 --> 38:11.000
The entire city participates in this extraordinary event.

38:12.000 --> 38:21.000
When the parade ends, everyone goes to the football stadium to watch the Rose Bowl game, the biggest sports event of the year.

38:21.000 --> 38:29.000
Another famous New Year's Day parade is the Macy's Day Parade in New York City.

38:29.000 --> 38:37.000
Many Americans watch this parade on television in the morning, and in the afternoon, they watch a football game.

38:42.000 --> 38:47.000
8. Chinese New Year

38:47.000 --> 38:55.000
Chinese New Year is the most important festivity for the Chinese people in America and Great Britain.

38:55.000 --> 39:02.000
It is also called the Spring Festival, or the Lunar New Year.

39:02.000 --> 39:08.000
The exact date on the Western calendar changes from year to year.

39:09.000 --> 39:16.000
However, Chinese New Year takes place between the 1st of January and the 19th of February.

39:16.000 --> 39:23.000
On the Chinese Lunar calendar, every month begins with the new moon.

39:24.000 --> 39:28.000
Every year has an animal's name.

39:29.000 --> 39:46.000
These animals are the rat, ox, tiger, rabbit, dragon, snake, horse, ram, monkey, rooster, dog, and pig.

39:46.000 --> 39:50.000
Sea Page 69

39:50.000 --> 39:56.000
A Chinese legend says that these 12 animals had a race.

39:56.000 --> 40:01.000
The first year was named after the rat, the winner.

40:01.000 --> 40:08.000
The other 11 years were named after the order in which the animals arrived in the race.

40:08.000 --> 40:21.000
The clever rat jumped onto the ox's back, then at the end jumped over the ox's head to arrive first.

40:22.000 --> 40:31.000
The Chinese believe that a person born in a particular year has some of the characteristics of that animal.

40:31.000 --> 40:37.000
Celebrations in Chinese families last for about two weeks.

40:37.000 --> 40:42.000
The celebrations begin with traditional house cleaning.

40:42.000 --> 40:47.000
The Chinese get rid of old and useless things.

40:47.000 --> 40:53.000
They do this to throw away the misfortunes of the past year.

40:53.000 --> 41:00.000
On Chinese New Year's Eve, all family members enjoy a big, delicious meal.

41:00.000 --> 41:07.000
It is very important for the Chinese to be with their families on this occasion.

41:07.000 --> 41:14.000
Fish is always part of the dinner because it represents abundance.

41:15.000 --> 41:22.000
On New Year's Day, all Chinese children wear new clothes with bright colours.

41:22.000 --> 41:26.000
Red is considered a lucky colour.

41:26.000 --> 41:35.000
Parents and relatives give children the traditional New Year's gift called Laisie, lucky money.

41:35.000 --> 41:40.000
This money is put into bright red and gold envelopes.

41:40.000 --> 41:48.000
Red is a traditional colour for festivals, celebrations, weddings and birthdays.

41:48.000 --> 41:54.000
In Britain, a parade takes place in Soho, London.

41:54.000 --> 41:59.000
This is one of the biggest parades in an English-speaking country.

41:59.000 --> 42:04.000
Dragon or lion dancers often lead the parade.

42:04.000 --> 42:09.000
In Chinatown, Soho, there are many Chinese restaurants.

42:09.000 --> 42:15.000
It is possible to stop and eat typical Chinese food.

42:15.000 --> 42:24.000
Chinese New Year was celebrated on the 21st of February 1851 for the first time in San Francisco.

42:24.000 --> 42:28.000
This was during the California Gold Rush.

42:28.000 --> 42:35.000
A lot of Chinese immigrants worked in California during the Gold Rush.

42:36.000 --> 42:43.000
In big American cities such as San Francisco, New York, Honolulu and Houston,

42:43.000 --> 42:50.000
Chinese New Year is a major event with wonderful parades.

42:50.000 --> 42:57.000
San Francisco, California has the biggest oriental community outside of Asia.

42:57.000 --> 43:02.000
This area of San Francisco is called Chinatown.

43:02.000 --> 43:08.000
There are many Chinese shops, restaurants and libraries in Chinatown.

43:08.000 --> 43:13.000
All street and shops signs are written in Chinese.

43:13.000 --> 43:21.000
During the Chinese New Year, Chinatown is decorated with beautiful ornaments.

43:21.000 --> 43:26.000
Most of the costumes and masks come from Hong Kong.

43:26.000 --> 43:34.000
Every year, there is a Miss Chinatown, USA beauty and talent contest.

43:34.000 --> 43:39.000
The lion dancers are always part of the festivities.

43:39.000 --> 43:48.000
The lion has a big head and long body made of cloth.

43:49.000 --> 43:56.000
The lion dance is accompanied by drums, cymbals and noisy firecrackers.

44:03.000 --> 44:10.000
According to ancient traditions, the great noise frightens away evil spirits.

44:11.000 --> 44:20.000
The dragon is the most important figure of the Chinese New Year festivities and parades.

44:20.000 --> 44:24.000
The dragon is considered a lucky figure.

44:24.000 --> 44:30.000
A parade dragon can be 20 to 30 meters long.

44:30.000 --> 44:38.000
60 or more men move under a long cloth that represents the dragon's tail.

44:39.000 --> 44:45.000
During the parade, children represent the animals of the Chinese calendar.

44:45.000 --> 44:51.000
There are also acrobats and musicians in beautiful costumes.

44:51.000 --> 44:57.000
Every year, the San Francisco parade attracts thousands of spectators.

44:57.000 --> 45:04.000
It is a magnificent event.

45:04.000 --> 45:09.000
Chapter 9 – Valentine's Day

45:09.000 --> 45:15.000
Valentine's Day, the 14th of February, is dedicated to people in love.

45:15.000 --> 45:23.000
On the 14th of February, sweethearts celebrate Valentine's Day with cards and presents.

45:23.000 --> 45:27.000
Cards can be funny, romantic or poetic.

45:27.000 --> 45:33.000
Presence can be a box of chocolates, flowers or jewelry.

45:33.000 --> 45:38.000
When and where did this festivity start?

45:38.000 --> 45:49.000
The custom of celebrating Valentine's Day probably began with the Roman festival of Lupercalia on the 15th of February.

45:49.000 --> 45:54.000
During Lupercalia, there were games and dancing.

45:54.000 --> 45:59.000
Every young man took the name of a young lady from an urn.

45:59.000 --> 46:05.000
The lady was the young man's sweetheart for one year.

46:05.000 --> 46:10.000
With the beginning of Christianity, pagan customs were not permitted.

46:10.000 --> 46:13.000
But the festival continued.

46:13.000 --> 46:20.000
In the 7th century, this festival was called St. Valentine's Day.

46:20.000 --> 46:23.000
The origin of the name is still a mystery.

46:24.000 --> 46:31.000
Some historians say that the festival took its name from a Christian martyr named Valentine.

46:31.000 --> 46:37.000
He died on the 14th of February in the year 270.

46:37.000 --> 46:46.000
Others say Valentine was put in prison by Emperor Claudius because he secretly married young couples.

46:46.000 --> 46:51.000
The emperor did not like these secret marriages.

46:51.000 --> 46:59.000
Some say that Valentine comes from the French word gallatin, a gallant or bow.

46:59.000 --> 47:05.000
A legend says that birds begin to mate on the 14th of February.

47:05.000 --> 47:09.000
The Roman conquerors brought the celebration to England.

47:09.000 --> 47:16.000
In England, the pagan and Christian customs combined to form the Valentine festivity.

47:17.000 --> 47:21.000
The Valentine tradition was popular in Shakespeare's time.

47:21.000 --> 47:28.000
Shakespeare's characters Romeo and Juliet are the eternal symbol of love.

47:28.000 --> 47:33.000
In the play Hamlet, Ophelia sang this song.

47:47.000 --> 47:55.000
In 17th century London, sweethearts exchanged presents on the 14th of February.

47:55.000 --> 48:01.000
The English settlers took this romantic tradition to the new world.

48:01.000 --> 48:06.000
Some settlers made beautiful Valentine's cards by hand.

48:06.000 --> 48:15.000
They painted butterflies, flowers, cupids and hearts on the cards, and then wrote original verses.

48:16.000 --> 48:21.000
In the 1800s, few people had time to make Valentine's cards.

48:21.000 --> 48:27.000
American manufacturers printed millions of romantic cards.

48:27.000 --> 48:34.000
The most popular cards had moving parts, windows that opened and showed a romantic poem,

48:34.000 --> 48:38.000
and little birds that seemed to fly.

48:38.000 --> 48:44.000
After the romantic Valentine, the comic Valentine became popular.

48:44.000 --> 48:50.000
It had funny cartoons or grotesque pictures with comic messages.

48:50.000 --> 48:54.000
Today, there are all types of Valentine's cards.

48:54.000 --> 49:04.000
Romantic, poetic, comic, grotesque, artistic and handmade.

49:04.000 --> 49:13.000
In 1947, the town of Loveland in Colorado, USA, became Cupid's residence.

49:13.000 --> 49:20.000
In Loveland, something very unusual happens about two weeks before Valentine's Day.

49:20.000 --> 49:30.000
The Loveland Post Office receives more than 300,000 Valentine's cards from all over the world.

49:30.000 --> 49:38.000
The Loveland Post Office cancels these cards with the Loveland, Colorado cancellation.

49:38.000 --> 49:44.000
A picture of Cupid and Romantic verses are stamped on the envelope.

49:44.000 --> 49:50.000
Then the Valentine's cards are sent to the address E.

49:50.000 --> 49:55.000
These are two examples of the Loveland verses.

49:55.000 --> 49:59.000
Across the land, we send hugs and kisses.

49:59.000 --> 50:07.000
From the sweetheart city, come Valentine wishes.

50:07.000 --> 50:18.000
Hope this special day will make you smile, and the love sent from Loveland will shorten each mile.

50:18.000 --> 50:26.000
If you want to use this unusual Valentine's service, write to the following address for more information.

50:26.000 --> 50:34.000
Ms. Julie Farnham, Visitor's Center, Valentine's cards.

50:34.000 --> 50:49.000
5400 Stone Creek Circle, Suite 100, Loveland, Colorado, 80538, USA.

50:49.000 --> 51:02.000
Telephone 001 880 258 1278.

51:02.000 --> 51:12.000
In Great Britain, it is customary to send an anonymous Valentine's card or present to the person you like or love.

51:12.000 --> 51:16.000
The person must guess who wrote it.

51:16.000 --> 51:22.000
Today, in the United States, Valentine's Day has a bigger meaning.

51:22.000 --> 51:31.000
On this day, you can send a card or a present to a parent, grandparent, relative or a friend.

51:31.000 --> 51:39.000
Valentine's Day is an occasion to express love or affection to anyone.

51:39.000 --> 51:48.000
In elementary school, American boys and girls write cards to their favorite classmates.

51:48.000 --> 51:53.000
Then they put them into a big box in the school hall.

51:53.000 --> 51:57.000
In the afternoon, there is a Valentine's Day party.

51:57.000 --> 52:03.000
The teacher takes the cards out of the box and gives them to the children.

52:03.000 --> 52:07.000
This is always an exciting moment.

52:07.000 --> 52:10.000
Children like counting their cards.

52:10.000 --> 52:21.000
Most children sign their Valentine's card, but some remain anonymous or write from a secret admirer.

52:21.000 --> 52:30.000
In American high schools and universities, there is a sweetheart's ball on the evening of the 14th of February.

52:30.000 --> 52:37.000
For the sweetheart's ball, the hall is decorated with red hearts and cupids.

52:37.000 --> 52:44.000
Some people have parties at home to celebrate this day dedicated to love.

52:44.000 --> 52:58.000
In the USA, the top of the Empire State Building in New York City is illuminated with red lights to celebrate Valentine's Day.

52:58.000 --> 53:04.000
Chapter 10 St. Patrick's Day

53:04.000 --> 53:14.000
In the United States and Great Britain, the Irish communities celebrate St. Patrick's Day on the 17th of March.

53:14.000 --> 53:20.000
The Irish community in the United States is very big.

53:20.000 --> 53:27.000
During the 1800s, thousands of Irish immigrants went to America.

53:27.000 --> 53:35.000
They settled in all parts of the country and took their traditions with them.

53:35.000 --> 53:42.000
Who was St. Patrick and why is he important to the Irish?

53:42.000 --> 53:47.000
St. Patrick is the patron of Ireland.

53:47.000 --> 53:53.000
He left several writings about his life and work in Ireland.

53:53.000 --> 54:00.000
Patrick was born in Britain in 389 A.D.

54:00.000 --> 54:05.000
His father was a landowner and a Christian.

54:05.000 --> 54:12.000
When Patrick was 16 years old, he was captured and taken to Ireland.

54:12.000 --> 54:15.000
He became a slave.

54:15.000 --> 54:20.000
After six years, Patrick escaped to France by ship.

54:20.000 --> 54:24.000
There, he became a priest.

54:24.000 --> 54:31.000
He returned to Ireland as a bishop in 432 A.D.

54:31.000 --> 54:35.000
His missionary work was very successful.

54:35.000 --> 54:40.000
He converted most of the Irish to Christianity.

54:40.000 --> 54:44.000
He was a generous and dedicated man.

54:44.000 --> 54:50.000
He introduced the Roman alphabet to Ireland.

54:50.000 --> 54:54.000
There are legends about St. Patrick.

54:54.000 --> 54:59.000
One legend says that he banished all the serpents from Ireland.

54:59.000 --> 55:07.000
Another legend says that he used a shamrock to teach the Irish about the Trinity.

55:07.000 --> 55:15.000
Today, the shamrock is still a symbol of Ireland and the Irish.

55:15.000 --> 55:28.000
St. Patrick died in 461 and his tomb at Down Patrick is a center of pilgrimage.

55:28.000 --> 55:37.000
Today, on the 17th of March, there are big parades in most American cities in honour of the Irish.

55:37.000 --> 55:47.000
Marching bands dressed in green play lively Irish music.

55:47.000 --> 55:54.000
The Irish community organises parades and other colourful events.

55:54.000 --> 56:00.000
American and British people wear green clothing on St. Patrick's Day.

56:00.000 --> 56:04.000
Most people wear a green shamrock.

56:04.000 --> 56:14.000
Many shops and restaurants are decorated with green shamrocks in honour of the Irish.

56:15.000 --> 56:22.000
Chapter 11 Easter Easter is a very important Christian

56:22.000 --> 56:24.000
festivity.

56:24.000 --> 56:31.000
People celebrate the resurrection of Jesus Christ on the third day after his death.

56:31.000 --> 56:37.000
Easter is celebrated on the first Sunday after the full moon in March.

56:37.000 --> 56:44.000
This is between the 22nd of March and the 25th of April.

56:44.000 --> 56:50.000
The origin of the English word Easter is uncertain.

56:50.000 --> 56:56.000
It probably comes from the pagan goddess of spring, Eostre.

56:56.000 --> 57:03.000
The pagan celebrated the arrival of spring with special festivals.

57:03.000 --> 57:11.000
The Christian Easter slowly replaced the pagan festivals, but some symbols of the spring festivals remained,

57:11.000 --> 57:17.000
such as flowers, eggs, rabbits and bunnies.

57:17.000 --> 57:21.000
The tradition of the Easter basket is ancient.

57:21.000 --> 57:29.000
The pagans offered their eggs in grass baskets to the goddess Eostre.

57:29.000 --> 57:39.000
In Britain and in the United States, it is usual to send Easter cards to friends and relatives.

57:39.000 --> 57:44.000
For most Christian families, Easter morning begins with a church service.

57:44.000 --> 57:49.000
Some Easter services begin very early in the morning.

57:49.000 --> 57:56.000
Others take place out of doors in a garden or park.

57:56.000 --> 58:03.000
Easter is a time for Christians to be happy, and there is special music in the churches.

58:03.000 --> 58:10.000
It is possible to hear George Frederick Handels messiah during some Easter services.

58:27.000 --> 58:38.000
To celebrate Easter and the arrival of spring, almost everyone wears something new.

58:38.000 --> 58:43.000
A new dress, a new suit, new shoes.

58:43.000 --> 58:51.000
Before Easter Day, American and British children paint Easter eggs with bright colors and designs.

58:51.000 --> 58:56.000
Colored eggs were exchanged at ancient spring festivals.

58:56.000 --> 59:01.000
The egg is an ancient symbol of life and fertility.

59:01.000 --> 59:07.000
The decoration of Easter eggs began in England during the Middle Ages.

59:07.000 --> 59:15.000
Members of noble families gave one another gold-covered eggs as Easter presents.

59:16.000 --> 59:25.000
On Easter Day in the United States, there is the traditional Easter egg hunt in every city and town.

59:25.000 --> 59:32.000
Parents tell their children that the Easter Bunny hid many eggs in the park.

59:32.000 --> 59:36.000
The children must find the hidden eggs.

59:36.000 --> 59:42.000
Eggs are hidden in the grass, in a shrub, or under a tree.

59:42.000 --> 59:48.000
When the children find the eggs, they put them in colorful Easter baskets.

59:48.000 --> 59:54.000
The child with the biggest number of eggs is the winner.

59:54.000 --> 01:00:05.000
The tradition of the Easter Bunny and the basket of eggs was introduced by German immigrants long ago.

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:10.000
On Easter Monday, children roll their eggs down a hill.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:14.000
Egg rolling is an ancient Easter tradition.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:21.000
The first egg that reaches the bottom of the hill without breaking is the winner.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:29.000
A famous egg rolling contest takes place outside the White House in Washington, D.C. on Easter Monday.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:38.000
The President of the United States invites children to roll eggs on the lawn of the White House.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:46.000
At Easter time, there are chocolate eggs, chocolate bunnies, and sugar eggs in all sweet shops.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:51.000
Some eggs are personalized with a name on them.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:55.000
Hot cross buns are a special Easter food.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:01:00.000
They are small sweet cakes with a cross on top.

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:05.000
This cross represents Christ's death on the cross.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:11.000
The buns are usually eaten in Britain on Good Friday.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:18.000
In many American cities and towns, there is an Easter bonnet parade.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:25.000
Girls and women with funny and bizarre Easter bonnets march in the parade.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:28.000
Most women make their own bonnets.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:32.000
There is a prize for the most original.

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:39.000
The most famous Easter bonnet parade is in New York City on Fifth Avenue.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:43.000
Thousands of people participate.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:53.000
In 1933, the great American composer Irving Berlin wrote a song about the Easter bonnet parade.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:56.000
Here is a verse.

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:05.000
In your Easter bonnet, with all the frills upon it,

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:15.000
you'll be the grandest lady in the Easter parade.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:21.000
Families usually spend Easter day together.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:34.000
The traditional Easter meal consists of roast lamb, peas, new potatoes, and eggs in many forms.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:40.000
Chapter 12, May Day

01:02:40.000 --> 01:02:47.000
On the first day of May, we celebrate the arrival of spring and warm weather.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:53.000
Everyone is happy to say goodbye to winter and to welcome spring.

01:02:53.000 --> 01:03:02.000
Flowers bloom, leaves grow, and baby animals are born in spring.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:11.000
The May Day festival originated in the Roman Empire in about 258 B.C.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:18.000
It was a festivity in honor of flora, the goddess of flowers and spring.

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:26.000
When the Romans invaded Britain, the festivity was celebrated by the Britons too.

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:32.000
The ancient Celts celebrated spring the night before May Day.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:36.000
This festival was called Beltane.

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:40.000
The druids made big fires on top of the hills.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:48.000
The Celts sat around the fires and ate, sang songs, and danced happily.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:55.000
In central Scotland, Beltane is still an important festival.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:04:02.000
In the Middle Ages, May Day was one of the merriest festivities in Britain.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:08.000
People went into the forest after midnight to pick flowers and plants.

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:14.000
They returned the next morning and put the leaves and flowers in their hair.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:21.000
There was music, singing and dancing all day.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:27.000
The most important event of the day was the dance around the May Pole.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:34.000
The most beautiful young woman of the village became the Queen of the May.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:38.000
There were morris dances too.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:46.000
In Britain, May Day is a public holiday and it is celebrated on the first Monday in May.

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:52.000
It is not a public holiday in the United States.

01:04:52.000 --> 01:05:00.000
In Britain and the United States, there are still traditional May Pole dances on May Day.

01:05:01.000 --> 01:05:05.000
People in costumes dance around the May Pole.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:10.000
The May Pole is decorated with many coloured ribbons.

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:18.000
The coloured ribbons represent the sun's rays and form a design on the May Pole.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:25.000
In Britain, many people in costumes do morris dancing on May Day.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:29.000
They dance with bells and handkerchiefs.

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:39.000
The tradition probably came from Spain in the 13th century, when it was called morris dancing.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:47.000
In the United States, most elementary schools celebrate May Day with dances around the May Pole.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:54.000
In some American towns and universities, there are May Day festivals.

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:58.000
A young woman becomes the May Queen.

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:04.000
Music, dancing around the May Pole and games are all part of the festival.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:09.000
There are beautiful floral decorations everywhere.

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:14.000
Chapter 13

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:17.000
Independence Day

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:26.000
The most animated American festivity is the 4th of July, or Independence Day.

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:29.000
It is the nation's birthday.

01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:34.000
The 4th of July is a salute to freedom and democracy.

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:43.000
It is a time to remember America's ideals of liberty, equality, and opportunity for all.

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:47.000
What happened on the 4th of July?

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:55.000
In the 1700s, the 13 American colonies belonged to Great Britain.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:06:59.000
The colonists did not want to be governed by Britain.

01:06:59.000 --> 01:07:04.000
They wanted to be independent and to choose their own government.

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:07.000
They wanted a democracy.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:13.000
Britain imposed high taxes, and there were many rebellions.

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:22.000
On the 4th of July, 1776, a group of patriots wrote the Declaration of Independence.

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:30.000
The Declaration proclaimed independence from Britain, and democracy and justice for all.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:40.000
With the Declaration of Independence, the 13 colonies created their own nation, the United States of America.

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:46.000
The Liberty Bell is a symbol of Independence Day.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:52.000
The Americans fought against the British in the American Revolution.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:08:02.000
After years of war, the British were defeated in 1781 in Yorktown, Virginia.

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:08.000
Today, Americans celebrate the 4th of July in many different ways.

01:08:08.000 --> 01:08:16.000
There is an American flag on every flagpole, and many people put a flag outside their window.

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:22.000
Americans call their flag the Stars and Stripes.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:27.000
Every city and town organizes its own celebration.

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:33.000
Red, white, and blue decorations fill the streets.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:46.000
Traditional 4th of July events are patriotic speeches, parades, baseball games, competitions, a lot of music, dancing and picnics.

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:50.000
These picnics are an old American tradition.

01:08:50.000 --> 01:09:01.000
The typical picnic consists of hamburgers, hot dogs, potato salad, chocolate cake, and ice cream.

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:10.000
The festivities usually end with a brilliant fireworks show.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:14.000
In the West, rodeos are a favorite event.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:20.000
A western rodeo is a spectacular event to watch.

01:09:20.000 --> 01:09:27.000
In Virginia, there are historic parades, with people in 18th century costumes.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:35.000
In New York City, the top of the Empire State Building is illuminated with red, white, and blue lights.

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:46.000
In Flagstaff, Arizona, American Indians celebrate with a three-day powwow, a rodeo, and tribal dances.

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:52.000
Bridgeport, California, is a small town in the Sierra Nevada Mountains.

01:09:52.000 --> 01:09:58.000
Bridgeport celebrates Independence Day in an old-fashioned way.

01:09:58.000 --> 01:10:06.000
Before the ten o'clock parade, someone reads the Declaration of Independence to the town.

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:16.000
Then cowboys and Indians from nearby ranches come to the town on their beautiful horses.

01:10:16.000 --> 01:10:20.000
Children ride decorated bicycles in the parade.

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:24.000
There is a big pie-eating competition.

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:31.000
After a delicious picnic of barbecued meat, there is a baseball game.

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:38.000
In the evening, there is country music and dancing.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:44.000
Chapter 14, Notting Hill Carnival

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:51.000
The Notting Hill Carnival of London is the second biggest carnival in the world,

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:56.000
and the biggest street festival in Europe.

01:10:56.000 --> 01:11:06.000
It is always on the last Sunday and Monday in August, which is a bank holiday, a public holiday, in the United Kingdom.

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:11.000
On Sunday, there is the children's carnival.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:16.000
The carnival takes place in Notting Hill, West London.

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:21.000
When did the first carnival take place?

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:30.000
In the 1950s, people from the Caribbean, and in particular from Trinidad, emigrated to Britain.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:36.000
They took their customs and traditions with them.

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:48.000
People remembered the great carnivals held in the West Indies, and in 1964, a street festival took place in Notting Hill.

01:11:48.000 --> 01:11:57.000
There were few people in costume dancing in the streets and carrying steel drums in this first festival.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:12:01.000
However, it was a great success.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:13.000
Since then, carnival has taken place every year in Notting Hill, and it has grown into an enormous multicultural arts festival.

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:20.000
Carnival celebrations normally take place before Easter in the month of March.

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:26.000
However, in Britain, these celebrations take place in August, when the weather is warmer.

01:12:26.000 --> 01:12:36.000
During the year, the West Indian families prepare their beautiful costumes and practice playing their steel drums.

01:12:36.000 --> 01:12:40.000
They also work on their floats.

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:51.000
On the days of carnival, Notting Hill is full of colour, excitement, music, noise and people.

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:57.000
About two million people go to carnival every year.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:13:10.000
People with wonderful costumes dance in the streets, and steel bands play Calypso, the traditional music of the West Indies.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:26.000
They also play soccer, the traditional music of carnival, a mixture of soul and Calypso.

01:13:28.000 --> 01:13:40.000
It is also possible to hear reggae, hip hop and jazz.

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:49.000
A parade with colourful floats travels seven and a half kilometres through the streets of London.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:54.000
There is a prize for the best float.

01:13:54.000 --> 01:14:00.000
It is sometimes almost impossible for the public to walk along the streets.

01:14:00.000 --> 01:14:04.000
The only way to move is to dance.

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:29.000
In the streets, food vendors sell meat and vegetable patties, salted fish and other delicious West Indian specialities.

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:33.000
Everyone has a good time.

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:10.000
Thanks for watching!

